{
  "texts": [
    "Since for any downset in ⟨S, ⊑⟩, its complement is an upset, and vice versa, the closed sets in O(S, ⊑) are just the upsets in ⟨S, ⊑⟩.",
    "Thus, the closure cl(X) of a set X, the smallest upset that includes X, is the set ⇑X = {y ∈ S | ∃x ⊑ y: x ∈ X} of all states with refinements in X; and the interior int(X) of X, the largest downset that is included in X, is the set {y ∈ S | ∀x ⊑ y: x ∈ X} (= S \\ ⇑(S \\ X)) of all states all of whose refinements are in X.",
    "(Note that in what follows, we sometimes apply the operations int and cl to sets X ⊆ S that are not downsets.)",
    "From this perspective, we can rewrite the ¬ and → clauses of Definition 2.3 equivalently as:• ¬φ M = int(S \\ φ M); • φ → ψ M = int((S \\ φ M) ∪ ψ M).Since the interior of the complement is the complement of the closure, we have int(S \\ φ M) = S \\ cl( φ M).",
    "So by the ¬ clause, we have ¬¬φ M = int(S \\ (S \\ cl( φ M))) = int(cl( φ M))."
  ]
}